142.title: The Voyage
notes: The Voyage / V. Segrelles. -- New York : NBM, 1995. -- 46 p. : col. ill. ; 28 cm. -- (The Mercenary) -- NBM numbering: 5. -- Translated into English by Lawrence Schimel. -- Call no.: PN6777.S4V613 1995

"Exoskeleton" 16 p. -- Summary: The Mercenary is flying over the ocean and spots an unfamiliar island. Landing to rest and get water, he rescues a telepathic winged woman from a giant spider's web, and while he's doing that a city of insect men steals his dragon. In order to get his dragon back he impersonates an insect lord, conveniently fulfilling a prophecy, and fights the king. The Mercenary boasts that he can do something the king cannot, and removes the breastplate of his armor. The king then removes the front plate of his exoskeleton, but after that he cannot fight. The insect men then realize that he is a human and attack, and as he is falling off a cliff towards the maw of a great big monster, four winged women catch him in midair, take him to his dragon, and send him on his way. The canteen of water they give him is deadly with radioactivity.

"The Flight" 7 p. -- Summary: From a tower on an island floating in the air, The Mercenary is determined to try Arnoldo Da Vinci's set of wings and fly under his own muscle power. Nan-Tay is worried, but The Mercenary kisses her and jumps anyway. The wings work, but suddenly as he's approaching the tower where he started, he starts to bleed and fall, and he heads for a lower landing far over the water. We see a young boy commenting to his Uncle Claust that the bird he just shot as target practice looked like a man flying.

"The Lighthouse" 21 p. -- Summary: The wings, the kiss, and the target practice were all a dream induced by the radioactive water. The dragon is also panicked and wounded, but they make it to an island with a lighthouse. The keepers communicate telepathically, giving him pills to counter the poisoning, and send them toward another island, smoking in the distance. Before they can leave, fearful refugees from that island land near them. They call this island The Black Isle, and are convinced spirits or ghosts will kill them for landing on it. The Mercenary leads an expedition back to the smoking island to which the lighthouse has moved. The lighthouse seems to have anti-gravity powers. Using the information gained telepathically he moves it back to The Black Isle, in turn causing a volcanic eruption which releases a ship of some kind from the insides of the island. For some reason the ship saves the island people and their boat from the tsunami wave caused by the eruption.

This summary is from European Comics in English Translation (Jefferson, NC : McFarland & Company, 2002). Used with permission.
